HYPERTENSION - COMPREHENSIVE CLINICAL REFERENCE
Based on ACC/AHA 2017 Hypertension Guidelines and JNC 8 Recommendations

SECTION 1: DEFINITIONS AND CLASSIFICATION

What is hypertension?
Hypertension is defined as persistently elevated blood pressure in the arteries. According to the 2017 ACC/AHA guidelines, hypertension is classified as blood pressure of 130/80 mmHg or greater. It is the most common modifiable cardiovascular risk factor, affecting approximately 1.28 billion adults worldwide and is responsible for 10.4 million deaths per year globally.

How is blood pressure classified?
Normal blood pressure is systolic below 120 mmHg and diastolic below 80 mmHg. Elevated blood pressure is systolic 120 to 129 mmHg and diastolic below 80 mmHg. Stage 1 hypertension is systolic 130 to 139 mmHg or diastolic 80 to 89 mmHg. Stage 2 hypertension is systolic 140 mmHg or greater or diastolic 90 mmHg or greater. Hypertensive crisis is systolic above 180 mmHg and/or diastolic above 120 mmHg.

What is the difference between hypertensive urgency and emergency?
Hypertensive urgency is severely elevated blood pressure above 180/120 mmHg without acute target organ damage. It does not require immediate intravenous treatment. Hypertensive emergency is severely elevated blood pressure with acute target organ damage including hypertensive encephalopathy, intracranial hemorrhage, acute coronary syndrome, acute pulmonary edema, acute aortic dissection, or acute kidney injury. It requires immediate IV treatment in an ICU setting.

What is white coat hypertension?
White coat hypertension is elevated blood pressure measured in a clinical setting with normal blood pressure outside the clinic. It affects 15 to 30% of patients with elevated office readings. It is diagnosed by ambulatory blood pressure monitoring showing average daytime readings below 135/85 mmHg. White coat hypertension carries a lower cardiovascular risk than sustained hypertension but higher risk than true normotension. Annual monitoring is recommended.

What is masked hypertension?
Masked hypertension is normal blood pressure in a clinical setting with elevated blood pressure outside the clinic. It is diagnosed by ambulatory monitoring. It affects 10 to 17% of the general population and carries similar cardiovascular risk to sustained hypertension. It is associated with end organ damage and increased cardiovascular events. It is more common in patients with diabetes, chronic kidney disease, and obstructive sleep apnea.

What is resistant hypertension?
Resistant hypertension is defined as blood pressure above goal despite use of 3 antihypertensive medications of different classes at maximum tolerated doses, including a diuretic. True resistant hypertension affects 10 to 20% of hypertensive patients. It requires evaluation for secondary causes, medication non-adherence, white coat effect, and drug interactions. Spironolactone is the most effective fourth-line agent for resistant hypertension.

SECTION 2: EPIDEMIOLOGY AND RISK FACTORS

How common is hypertension?
Hypertension affects approximately 47% of US adults or 116 million people using the 2017 ACC/AHA definition. Prevalence increases with age affecting over 70% of adults over 65. It is more prevalent in Black Americans than White Americans. Control rates remain suboptimal with only 24% of hypertensive adults having well-controlled blood pressure globally.

What are the risk factors for developing hypertension?
Non-modifiable risk factors include age, family history, race particularly Black race, and male sex under age 55. Modifiable risk factors include obesity, physical inactivity, high sodium diet, excessive alcohol consumption, tobacco use, chronic stress, sleep apnea, and low potassium intake. Secondary causes including kidney disease, primary aldosteronism, and endocrine disorders account for 5 to 10% of hypertension cases.

SECTION 3: DIAGNOSIS AND MEASUREMENT

How should blood pressure be measured correctly?
Accurate blood pressure measurement requires the patient to be seated quietly for at least 5 minutes with feet flat on the floor, back supported, and arm at heart level. An appropriately sized cuff covering 80% of the arm circumference should be used. Two readings should be taken at least 1 minute apart and averaged. Both arms should be measured at the initial visit — a difference greater than 10 mmHg warrants further evaluation for subclavian artery disease.

What is ambulatory blood pressure monitoring?
Ambulatory blood pressure monitoring involves wearing a device that automatically measures blood pressure every 15 to 30 minutes over 24 hours during normal daily activities including sleep. It provides average daytime and nighttime readings and identifies white coat hypertension, masked hypertension, and non-dipping patterns. A non-dipping pattern with less than 10% nocturnal blood pressure reduction is associated with higher cardiovascular risk and may indicate sleep apnea or secondary hypertension.

What is home blood pressure monitoring?
Home blood pressure monitoring is recommended using a validated upper arm device. The protocol involves measuring twice in the morning before medication and twice in the evening for 7 consecutive days. Discard the first day readings and average the remaining values. Home readings above 135/85 mmHg are considered hypertensive. Home monitoring improves medication adherence and is useful for evaluating treatment response.

When should secondary hypertension be suspected?
Secondary hypertension should be suspected in patients with onset before age 30, resistant hypertension, acute onset of hypertension, worsening of previously controlled hypertension, hypokalemia without diuretic use, abdominal bruit suggesting renovascular disease, and signs of endocrine disorders. The most common secondary causes are primary aldosteronism, renovascular hypertension, obstructive sleep apnea, chronic kidney disease, and thyroid disease.

SECTION 4: TARGET ORGAN DAMAGE

What cardiac damage does hypertension cause?
Hypertension is the most important risk factor for left ventricular hypertrophy, which is an independent predictor of cardiovascular events. It accelerates coronary artery disease, increases risk of myocardial infarction, and contributes to heart failure with preserved ejection fraction. Aortic valve disease and aortic aneurysm are also associated with chronic hypertension. Electrocardiographic or echocardiographic LVH should be sought at diagnosis and monitored during treatment.

What neurological damage does hypertension cause?
Hypertension is the most important modifiable risk factor for stroke, both ischemic and hemorrhagic. It causes lacunar infarcts, white matter hyperintensities, and contributes to vascular dementia. Hypertensive retinopathy with arteriovenous nicking, copper wiring, and papilledema reflects end organ damage. Fundoscopic examination can provide non-invasive assessment of vascular damage.

What renal damage does hypertension cause?
Hypertension is both a cause and consequence of chronic kidney disease creating a vicious cycle. It causes nephrosclerosis and is the second leading cause of end-stage renal disease after diabetes. Microalbuminuria is an early marker of hypertensive nephropathy. ACE inhibitors and ARBs are preferred in hypertension with proteinuria due to renal protective effects beyond blood pressure lowering.

SECTION 5: NON-PHARMACOLOGIC TREATMENT

What lifestyle modifications are recommended for hypertension?
Evidence-based lifestyle modifications include weight loss targeting normal BMI which reduces systolic blood pressure by 5 mmHg per 5 kg lost, DASH diet rich in fruits vegetables and low-fat dairy which reduces systolic by 8 to 14 mmHg, sodium restriction below 2.3 g/day which reduces systolic by 2 to 8 mmHg, regular aerobic exercise 90 to 150 minutes per week reducing systolic by 4 to 9 mmHg, limiting alcohol to 2 drinks per day for men and 1 for women reducing systolic by 2 to 4 mmHg, and smoking cessation.

What is the DASH diet?
The Dietary Approaches to Stop Hypertension diet emphasizes fruits and vegetables 8 to 10 servings daily, low-fat dairy 2 to 3 servings daily, whole grains, lean proteins, and limited sodium saturated fat and added sugars. It is rich in potassium, magnesium, calcium, and fiber. The DASH diet reduces systolic blood pressure by 8 to 14 mmHg, making it as effective as a single antihypertensive medication in some patients.

What is the role of sodium restriction in hypertension?
Dietary sodium restriction below 2.3 g per day or ideally below 1.5 g per day reduces blood pressure in most patients. Salt sensitivity is more common in Black Americans, older adults, obese patients, and those with diabetes or kidney disease. The blood pressure reduction from sodium restriction is additive with antihypertensive medications. Most dietary sodium comes from processed foods rather than added salt.

What is the effect of physical activity on blood pressure?
Regular aerobic exercise including walking, running, cycling, and swimming reduces systolic blood pressure by 4 to 9 mmHg. Resistance training provides additional benefit. Exercise training reduces blood pressure through multiple mechanisms including reduced sympathetic nervous system activity, improved endothelial function, and reduced arterial stiffness. Exercise should be performed most days of the week for sustained benefit.

SECTION 6: PHARMACOLOGIC TREATMENT

What are the first-line antihypertensive medications?
Four medication classes are considered first-line for most patients: thiazide and thiazide-like diuretics including chlorthalidone and hydrochlorothiazide, calcium channel blockers including amlodipine and nifedipine, ACE inhibitors including lisinopril and ramipril, and angiotensin receptor blockers including losartan and valsartan. Combination therapy is often required as most patients need more than one agent.

When are thiazide diuretics preferred?
Thiazide diuretics are effective first-line agents recommended for most patients without compelling indications for other drug classes. Chlorthalidone is preferred over hydrochlorothiazide as it has a longer duration of action and superior evidence for cardiovascular risk reduction from the ALLHAT trial. Thiazides are particularly effective in Black Americans and older adults. They are relatively inexpensive and generally well tolerated.

When are ACE inhibitors preferred?
ACE inhibitors are preferred in patients with diabetes and microalbuminuria due to renoprotective effects beyond blood pressure lowering, chronic kidney disease with proteinuria, systolic heart failure, recent myocardial infarction, and high cardiovascular risk. They block conversion of angiotensin I to angiotensin II reducing vasoconstriction and aldosterone secretion. ACE inhibitor induced cough occurs in 10 to 15% of patients and is more common in Asian patients.

When are ARBs preferred?
ARBs are preferred alternatives to ACE inhibitors in patients who develop ACE inhibitor cough or angioedema. They have equivalent cardiovascular and renal protective effects. The combination of ACE inhibitor and ARB is not recommended due to increased adverse effects without additional benefit. ARBs are preferred in patients with heart failure with reduced ejection fraction who cannot tolerate ACE inhibitors.

When are calcium channel blockers preferred?
Dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers including amlodipine and nifedipine are preferred in patients who are Black or elderly, patients with angina pectoris as they provide symptomatic relief, patients with isolated systolic hypertension, and patients with Raynaud's phenomenon. Non-dihydropyridine calcium channel blockers including diltiazem and verapamil are preferred in patients with atrial fibrillation requiring rate control.

When are beta-blockers used in hypertension?
Beta-blockers are not recommended as first-line therapy for uncomplicated hypertension. They are preferred in patients with coronary artery disease, recent myocardial infarction, systolic heart failure, atrial fibrillation requiring rate control, and migraine prophylaxis. Carvedilol and metoprolol succinate are preferred in heart failure. Beta-blockers should not be abruptly discontinued due to risk of rebound hypertension and angina.

What is the role of aldosterone antagonists in hypertension?
Spironolactone is the most effective fourth-line agent for resistant hypertension, reducing systolic blood pressure by 20 to 25 mmHg in resistant cases. It is particularly effective in patients with primary aldosteronism, obesity, and sleep apnea. Eplerenone has similar efficacy with fewer hormonal side effects. Potassium and renal function must be monitored as hyperkalemia can occur particularly with concurrent ACE inhibitor or ARB use.

SECTION 7: HYPERTENSIVE EMERGENCIES

What is the management of hypertensive emergency?
Hypertensive emergency requires immediate admission to an intensive care unit with continuous blood pressure monitoring. The goal is to reduce MAP by no more than 25% in the first hour, then to 160/100 to 110 mmHg over the next 2 to 6 hours, with further reduction to target over the next 24 to 48 hours. Overly rapid reduction can precipitate ischemic stroke, acute coronary syndrome, or renal failure.

What IV medications are used for hypertensive emergency?
First-line agents include intravenous labetalol which provides both alpha and beta blockade with a smooth predictable response, nicardipine a calcium channel blocker with titratable IV formulation preferred in neurological emergencies and perioperative hypertension, and clevidipine an ultra-short-acting calcium channel blocker easily titratable. Nitroprusside is effective but requires careful monitoring for cyanide toxicity particularly with prolonged infusion or renal impairment.

How is hypertensive encephalopathy managed?
Hypertensive encephalopathy presents with severe hypertension, headache, altered mental status, visual changes, and seizures. Brain MRI may show posterior reversible encephalopathy syndrome with white matter changes in posterior regions. Treatment involves labetalol or nicardipine IV with target MAP reduction of 25% in the first hour. Nimodipine is used specifically for hypertension associated with subarachnoid hemorrhage to prevent cerebral vasospasm.

SECTION 8: SECONDARY HYPERTENSION

What is primary aldosteronism?
Primary aldosteronism is the most common secondary cause of hypertension affecting 5 to 10% of hypertensive patients. It is caused by autonomous aldosterone secretion most commonly from bilateral adrenal hyperplasia or adrenal adenoma. It presents with hypertension, hypokalemia, and metabolic alkalosis. Screening uses the aldosterone to renin ratio. Bilateral hyperplasia is treated medically with spironolactone. Unilateral adenoma can be cured with adrenalectomy.

What is renovascular hypertension?
Renovascular hypertension results from renal artery stenosis causing activation of the renin-angiotensin-aldosterone system. It should be suspected in patients with onset of hypertension before age 30 or after age 55, flash pulmonary edema, abdominal bruit, resistant hypertension, and acute kidney injury with ACE inhibitor or ARB use. Causes include fibromuscular dysplasia in young women and atherosclerosis in older patients. Doppler ultrasound, CT angiography, or MR angiography are used for diagnosis.

What is the relationship between sleep apnea and hypertension?
Obstructive sleep apnea is present in 30 to 40% of hypertensive patients and is a major reversible cause of resistant hypertension. Repeated episodes of nocturnal hypoxia activate the sympathetic nervous system, raise blood pressure, and disrupt the normal nocturnal dipping pattern. CPAP therapy reduces blood pressure by 2 to 3 mmHg on average with greater reductions in patients with severe apnea and drug-resistant hypertension.

SECTION 9: SPECIAL POPULATIONS

How is hypertension managed in pregnancy?
Chronic hypertension in pregnancy is defined as hypertension present before 20 weeks gestation or persisting beyond 12 weeks postpartum. Preeclampsia is new onset hypertension above 140/90 mmHg after 20 weeks with proteinuria or end organ damage. Safe antihypertensives in pregnancy include labetalol, nifedipine, and methyldopa. ACE inhibitors and ARBs are contraindicated due to fetal toxicity. Severe hypertension above 160/110 requires urgent treatment to prevent stroke and placental abruption.

How is hypertension managed in elderly patients?
Elderly patients with hypertension benefit significantly from treatment with reductions in stroke, heart failure, and death. The SPRINT trial demonstrated benefits of intensive systolic target below 120 mmHg in adults over 75 though the ACCORD trial showed no benefit in diabetic patients. Start with lower doses and titrate slowly to minimize orthostatic hypotension which increases fall risk. Thiazide diuretics, ACE inhibitors, ARBs, and calcium channel blockers are all appropriate first-line agents in elderly patients.

How is hypertension managed in chronic kidney disease?
Blood pressure target in CKD is below 130/80 mmHg. ACE inhibitors or ARBs are preferred due to renoprotective effects and reduction in proteinuria. Combination ACE inhibitor plus ARB is not recommended. Thiazide diuretics have reduced efficacy with eGFR below 30 and loop diuretics are preferred for volume management. Aldosterone antagonists should be used cautiously due to risk of hyperkalemia. Renal function and electrolytes require close monitoring with initiation and dose changes.

How is hypertension managed in patients with diabetes?
Blood pressure target in diabetes is below 130/80 mmHg. ACE inhibitors or ARBs are preferred particularly in patients with microalbuminuria or macroalbuminuria. SGLT2 inhibitors have modest blood pressure lowering effects and provide additional cardiovascular and renal protection. Thiazide diuretics can worsen glucose control at higher doses. Beta-blockers may mask hypoglycemia symptoms and blunt the counter-regulatory response.

SECTION 10: CARDIOVASCULAR RISK REDUCTION

How does treating hypertension reduce cardiovascular risk?
Reducing systolic blood pressure by 10 mmHg reduces risk of major cardiovascular events by 20%, coronary heart disease by 17%, stroke by 27%, heart failure by 28%, and all-cause mortality by 13%. These benefits are consistent across age groups, levels of cardiovascular risk, and antihypertensive drug classes. The absolute benefit of treatment is greatest in patients at highest baseline cardiovascular risk.

What is the cardiovascular risk calculator used in hypertension management?
The ACC/AHA Pooled Cohort Equations calculate 10-year atherosclerotic cardiovascular disease risk using age, sex, race, total cholesterol, HDL cholesterol, systolic blood pressure, diabetes status, and smoking status. Patients with 10-year risk above 10% benefit from blood pressure treatment even at lower blood pressure levels. Risk calculators guide the decision to initiate pharmacologic therapy in Stage 1 hypertension.
